I think a lot about millennials who were the last generation to be able to create connections with artists, without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We would dive directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without having any reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundation for our lives.
That's why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the show every Thursday.
it looked nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specified closed places.
unconsciously we long to connect to the universal community surrounding all of this
that's why so many of us watch shows like The Office or movies like The Front Man with obsessive devotion, full of short references, like memes.
we repeated these references, knowing that most people knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
there are too many things to see and no way to rationalize everything... will we escape hypersaturation?
we get caught up in cycles of discovering new media, only to end up realizing that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
we are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
we enter parasocial relationships with more attention.
we understand that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
due to a lack of collective awareness about media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us stay critical.
some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall from it.
we are in a turbulent period and I'm eager to find out where it will take us.
